[***Problem 6. Create a graphic of the homeruns and stolen bases by salary in a year.***]{style="color:royalblue;"}

Power and Speed are two skills that are rarely displayed by the same player. For example, Shohei Ohtani was the first "50-50" player having more than 50 homeruns (power) and more than 50 stolen bases (speed). If this is a highly valued skill it may translate into higher paid players

We learned about the `Batting` dataset above and will use `HR` and `SB`.

```{r}
# Look at the Salaries dataset
glimpse(Salaries)
```

Thinking:

-   join `Batting` and `Salaries`

-   the `Salaries` dataset is incomplete with `NA` for player-year where it is not available (remove these rows)

-   create a new column `tier` that is a `factor` with levels `<$1MM`, `$1MM - $5MM`, `>$5MM` ("\$MM" is million USD) using `case_when`

Note: to add a reference line where homeruns and stolen bases are equal, look at `geom_abline` (it's used in the book example <https://r4ds.hadley.nz/numbers.html#center> )

**Note:** You will need to set `eval: true` when you have an answer you want to try out.

```{r}
#clean our data and hit it with an na.omit
SalariesClean <- Salaries |>
  filter(!is.na(salary))
#join it all together
BattingSalaries <- Batting |>
  inner_join(SalariesClean, by = c("playerID", "yearID", "teamID"))
# create tier column for bullet pt 3
BattingSalaries <- BattingSalaries |>
  mutate(tier = case_when(
    salary < 1e6 ~ "<$1MM",
    salary >= 1e6 & salary <= 5e6 ~ "$1MM - $5MM",
    salary > 5e6 ~ ">$5MM"
  ))
#wrap it all up
print(BattingSalaries)
```

[***Problem 7. For players who receive the Gold Glove Awards, compute the total HRs by year and then plot.***]{style="color:royalblue;"}

In early baseball there was an accepted trade-off between offense and defense skills. Over time some players are excelling at both. The Gold Glove awards recognize the best defensive players at each position and homeruns measure offense.

Datasets to use:

We learned about the `AwardsPlayers` dataset and the `Batting` dataset above.

Thinking:

-   filter `AwardsPlayers` to a Gold Glove winners

    -   note: the `AwardsPlayers` dataset has many different awards among the rows, and you only want rows with `awardID` matching `Gold Glove`

-   join result with `Batting` to create the dataset `GG_hr`

    -   note: each row of both datatsets is a player-year so the join needs to match on both keys using the argument `by = c("playerID", "yearID")`

-   compute the number of homeruns for each year using `group_by` with `yearID` and `summarize` with the `sum` function

-   make a time series plot of `ASG_hr` with `yearID` on the horizontal axis and the number of homeruns on the vertical axis

**Note:** You will need to set `eval: true` when you have an answer you want to try out.

First create `GG_hr`

```{r}
GG_hr <- function(AwardsPlayers, Batting) {
  GoldGloveWinners <- AwardsPlayers |>
    filter(awardID == "Gold Glove")
  GG_hr_data <- GoldGloveWinners |>
    inner_join(Batting, by = c("playerID", "yearID")) |>
    group_by(yearID) |>
    summarize(total_HR = sum(HR, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = "drop")
  return(GG_hr_data)
}
```

Then create graphic

```{r}
library(ggplot2)

GG_hr_data <- GG_hr(AwardsPlayers, Batting)

ggplot(GG_hr_data, aes(x = yearID, y = total_HR)) +
  geom_line(color = "blue", size = 1) +
  geom_point(color = "red", size = 2) +
  labs(
    title = "Home Runs by Gold Glove Winners Over Time",
    x = "Year",
    y = "Total Home Runs"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()
```

